Frank Rosenblatt's 1957 "Mark-1" hardware, the Perceptron, was an early neural network for recognizing geometric shapes. It had 400 inputs and one output, using weights as potentiometers. The New York Times predicted it could evolve into a conscious computer. The Perceptron is a binary classifier trained by adjusting weights with gradient descent.
